A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that fits in the dashboard of each car.
The devices, which record every mile driven and report the information to authorities, are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and the state planning offices to overhaul the outdated system to fund U.S. roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly ignited an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups and advocate that the government use the small boxes to record the kilometres driven – and possibly also where they have been driven – and then use the information to calculate tax returns.
The tea party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
But while it is not possible to agree on a course of action in Congress, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently looking at how they can switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
“It’s nothing we’re only likely to use,” said Hasan Ikhrata, managing director of the Southern California Assn. of Governments, which plans to record mileage for all California motorists in the state from 2025.
The way we pay these taxes is going to change.
The technology for that is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, funded by taxes paid by Americans at the gas pillar, is bankrupt.
But in America, there is not as much tanking as before.
Cars consume less gasoline.
The state mineral oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 eurocents per liter) has not risen in 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax even by one cent at high liquor prices.
“The gas tax is simply not future-proof,” said Lee Munnich, an expert on traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
His state has recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
“This is the most sensible long-term alternative,” he said.
Bureaucrats refer to it as mileage-based user fees.
It is not surprising that the idea is popular with urban liberals, because, for example, the tax could be used to influence driving behavior in such a way that congestion and climate-damaging exhaust gases are reduced.
California planners rely on the system to develop strategies to achieve the state’s ambitious, legally enshrined climate change goals.
But Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, also said he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also inspired by the idea of having drivers pay for the distance covered.
“This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” explains Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The move is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to move toward mileage-based billing.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have included 10,000 cars.
However, the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the advance and thus responded to the concerns of MPs from rural areas, who represent people who often have to travel many miles on the way to work or to the city in everyday life.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are moving in this direction on their own.
The most dedicated is Oregon, which is currently recruiting 5,000 drivers for the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees to the state instead of the mineral oil tax.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering this.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is currently investigating how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the devices, motorists were skeptical of the idea that the government could track any of their movements.
“Concerns about Big Brother and things like that were a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and results management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
When the test began, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into adult surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to capture data about the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to track mileage, but not exactly when and where.
This, according to Khan, would also reassure the public.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company originally did not join to help states in taxing motorists.
Rather, it was their goal to take a foothold in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers are to pay based on the miles driven.
However, the devices tested by her are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information, which is regularly uploaded by modem.
“People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Some of these public pilot programs have made big mistakes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, the planners are experimenting with giving drivers a number of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they choose no device at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the average miles traveled by all residents of the state.
Other agencies hope to be able to sell the concept to a distrustful public by equipping the devices with more features than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a device for taxation that also pays parking fees, only has to pay for mileage, and collect real-time speed data from other vehicles, thanks to which drivers can avoid traffic jams.
“Car drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system,” the city’s planning document said.
However, some traffic planners wonder if all the talk about paying per mile isn’t just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay Area, officials stated that Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising the fuel tax.
An additional one-off charge or annual fee could be imposed on drivers with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little gasoline, so that they also pay a fair share.
“There’s no reason for an operation if an aspirin is enough,” said Randy Rentschler, the Commission’s head of legislation and public affairs.
When we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers worry about their privacy and numerous other things.
