Esa decides on large space missions: missions for billions
Remote planets, gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they want to launch in the coming years.
Thirty proposals were available, five are still in the race.
Far worlds.
More than 1,000 planets in other stars have already been found by astronomers.
Whether there is life on at least some of them, no one knows.
The choice is difficult: Should you look for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or are you searching for Earth-like planets and perhaps discovering extraterrestrial life?
These questions are currently being asked by the European Space Agency (ESA).
For their "Cosmic Vision" program, they are looking for ideas for two large space projects that will drive research forward decisively.
The state for such "L-missions" is each about one billion euros.
The start is expected to be 2028 and 2034.
In early September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were debated, five of which have now entered the narrower elections.
Numerous committees examined the proposals, followed by the researchers.
In the next few days, a final decision will be made by the Scientific Program Committee.
In total, ESA has selected four major questions to be answered by the missions of the Cosmic Vision programme initiated in 2007.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes involved in the formation of stars from large gas clouds – and thus also the formation of planets circling these stars – are still in the proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life be created there?
To answer this question, the Cheops Space Telescope is scheduled to launch in 2017, which will take a closer look at 500 known planetary systems in our immediate vicinity.
However, the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could image Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, thus searching for “biomarkers”: gases that are considered an indicator of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question is also intended to provide insight into what conditions exist for the emergence of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field and the particle radiation emitted by it with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be investigated by example.
With the "Solar Orbiter", the ESA has already approved a mission of the M-Class (there is a budget of about half a billion euros) for this issue.
The probe is expected to launch in 2017 and closely observe the surface and activity of the Sun.
Of great interest to the researchers are also Jupiter and its moons.
They want to find out what role the giant planet has played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, the Esa envisages the first of the three L missions of the "Cosmic Vision" program.
The Juice (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) spacecraft is expected to launch in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and is supposed to study the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moons Europa, Kallisto and Ganymede.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many opportunities to study matter under extreme conditions and to examine whether the laws of nature we know are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could lead physicists to a new theory under whose roof all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the matter common to us, from which stars, planets and living beings like us consist, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and galaxy clusters together, and dark energy, through whose actions the expansion of the universe accelerates.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of a second of the explosion, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With "Euclid", the ESA has already approved an M-mission, the launch of which is scheduled for 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is intended to study the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the entire sky, thus allowing conclusions on the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could do the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
In the opinion of many experts, "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves, has the best chance of being granted an L-mission.
Among them, physicists understand changes in the structure of space-time that Albert Einstein had predicted nearly 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could do that, the scientists behind the project hope.
The mission envisions a detector consisting of two or three probes stationed in space.
It could also detect gravitational waves, unlike plants on Earth, that formed during the Big Bang, and thus provide new insights into the origin of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are still competing for the second L-mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which is intended to explore black holes, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Find".
Proposals have already been made, among other things, for the return of samples from Mars, for the exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids, as well as for solar physics.
