Frontier Airlines Charges for Hand Luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to demand up to $100 from passengers who want to store hand luggage on their flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 for one piece of hand luggage and $2 for coffee or lemonade, even though the announcement on Wednesday read that passengers are allowed to keep the entire can.
The new fee applies to hand luggage in the luggage compartment above the seat, small bags under the seat are still free of charge.
Frontier explained that they charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 for travelers who only paid at the flight deck.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O’Malley said the $100 fee was aimed at moving travelers to take care of the payment in advance.
“We don’t want to calculate that amount,” she said.
Airlines began charging fees for the first and second pieces of checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to bypass them have therefore packed as much as possible in their hand luggage, which means that the luggage compartments above the seat are often crowded.
Fees are a way to encourage passengers to take less on board.
O'Malley said the new fee isn't really about making money.
These are Frontier’s most loyal customers, who have made it clear that it will be increasingly difficult to find a place in the compartment above the seat.
Passengers who purchase their tickets on the airline’s website do not have to pay.
This means that a passenger may be allowed to carry a piece of luggage free of charge at Frontier’s flight deck, but the next person will have to pay $100 for a similar piece of luggage.
O’Malley said Frontier’s website and check-in procedures would be changed so that passengers would be informed of the fee before they arrive at the flight deck.
Frontier’s new hand luggage charge only comes into effect in the summer, an exact date is not yet available.
Passengers often complain about baggage charges and other charges, but airlines like to resort to them.
They argue that transporting the luggage costs money and passengers should pay for this service if they wanted it.
Many on Wall Street see the new baggage charges as a sign that airlines are taking enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
Most, however, so far leave the finger of charges for hand luggage.
Spirit Airlines Inc. first charged for hand luggage three years ago and later followed Allegiant Air, also a low-cost airliner.
The only other airline with such a fee is the Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the additional fees.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that Spirit’s hand luggage fee would bring in $50 million annually.
Sorensen, who previously held a leadership position at Midwest Airlines, recently flew with Spirit and was curious about what he would expect at the flight deck if passengers were confronted with the company’s unusual carry-on baggage charge.
“The boarding process was one of the most seamless I have experienced in my career in aviation,” he said.
I expected to see gnashing of teeth and tangible discussions on the flight deck.
“The plane was full,” he explained, “and the boarding was running like butter.”
Frontier also follows Spirit with the $2 required for coffee, tea, lemonade or juice.
The company explained that passengers who bought lemonade or juice should keep the whole can and coffee will be refilled for free.
Water is still free.
US Airways had briefly attempted to demand money for soft drinks in 2008, but seven months later it reversed this after passengers had complained and no other major company had relocated.
Frontier’s move to charge for hand luggage if passengers do not buy directly from the airline is the latest initiative to direct customers to their own website.
Airlines pay online travel agencies like Orbitz for $10 to $25 per ticket sold.
This provides an incentive for all companies to move passengers to buy directly from them instead of through an online travel agency.
Frontier, however, has gone the farthest in this area.
In September, the company began to award only half as many frequent flyer miles when booking via an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, the miles were once again reduced to 25 percent of the flight distance.
A flight with Frontier over 1000 miles, booked with a third party provider, therefore only brings in 250 miles for customers.
Passengers can also reserve seats exclusively for direct purchases on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base at its Denver headquarters, but the business is shrinking and the company is losing money.
Revenues fell by 9 percent and flight capacity shrank by almost 13 percent in the first quarter, according to the financial report released on Wednesday by its parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic has tried to get control of Frontier’s finances as part of the sale of the company.
