The lawyer returned home, picked up the drugs and then nine messages were exchanged between the two.
In court, it was revealed that Ditta was a “regular user” of cocaine after class A drugs were discovered in his hair, wallet, and credit cards during tests.
Ditta was later arrested, but declined to take cocaine, saying he had spoken to the alleged dealer because he was his client, claiming her discussion was subject to the "lawyer's secret."
During his arrest, Ditta took his wallet and tried to remove a series of credit cards, but they were secured and a hair sample was taken from him.
At the police interrogation, he stated that he operates both under his private address and at work, and clients would call him at home for legal matters.
In court, it became known that he had called important actors of the drug trade, some of whom he had represented previously, after significant arrests and informed about what the investigators knew about them.
Prosecutor Anne Whyte said: “A criminal attorney should know better than anyone else that you’re not breaking the law.”
Ditta is accused of abusing his position as a criminal defender because he has become too involved with certain clients.
The relationship in question is not simply that of a drug dealer, but of a drug dealer who supplies his lawyer with drugs.
Some of his communications were undoubtedly legitimate, as he was the lawyer for these individuals.
But this went far beyond the limits of a normal relationship between a lawyer and a client.
He acted against the police investigations as far as possible so that they could continue to pursue their criminal activities.
Mr. Ditta brought his professional status into disrepute.
He stood too close to certain clients, especially Scarborough, and he allowed his independence to be compromised.
Ditta denied any misconduct and claimed, “If I was a corrupt lawyer who I am not and wanted to pass on information to Scarborough, then I would not wait 15 hours, but do it immediately.”
