What happens to my e-mail on the way?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
Was the letter secret technically implemented in the design of the Internet service, similar to the traditional post?
When designing the early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols have not been careful to create a stable foundation for a hearing-proof correspondence.
Therefore, a conventional email is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
If user "Anna" sends an email to "Benni", are the computers of the two directly connected?
In the first step, Anna’s email program or browser sends the email to the mail server of her service provider.
For example, if it has a Gmail account, it would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider Benni uses.
On the route, the mail can run over several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content to his provider.
Are traditional emails being read along the way through the web?
Most emails are read multiple times by software robots on the go.
The sender’s provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the receiver systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam message, which is immediately deleted or at least sorted away in a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
In systems such as GMail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to place contextual advertising.
When Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google can display corresponding links to holiday offers.
Do unfamiliar people read the emails?
The likelihood of unauthorized persons reading an email is extremely low.
Theoretically, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
Law enforcement and intelligence agencies also have legal means to intercept or take note of emails.
This includes possible illegal espionage actions.
Is it possible to protect emails from co-reading?
With an encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an email can be effectively encrypted against co-reading.
With high technical effort, it is also possible to hide the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even possible to easily identify who has communicated with whom.
