George Kerevan: European decoupling gives Scots the choice
A new day, a new horror story about independence.
This time, we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition for EU membership.
This provides the key word for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a barbed wire secured border along the Hadrian's Wall.
In fact, the Strathclyde template pointed to the potential economic benefits that would bring more freedom to travel in the rest of Europe, but this did not – as expected – play a role in the headlines.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU Member States often flex their strict rules when it is more favourable to them.
Since Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, the continued non-observance of Brussels would be only a small concession in return for what is really wanted from the Scots.
So not really a story.
And one that has come so far that it already resembles a fossil: the first time I heard the “independence means passport control” duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to dance after the European pipe?
Why is the London yoke interchangeable with that of Brussels, especially now?
These are the real European news: the great post-war plan for the unification of Europe has fallen into disrepair.
With the Eurocrisis, the project Europe has officially died.
Everywhere in the EU, parties are gaining ground that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded only this year – was able to garner almost five million votes in the Bundestag elections in September, effectively expelling the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis turns out to be a turning point.
Due to the strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in connection with the forced jacket, into which the respective national economy is forced by the retention of the single currency, many people believe that the project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – this was the case only in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has fixed its members on exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters – and German politicians would like to let that happen.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the local currency, southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage over Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – prompted by Berlin.
Behind the current state and currency problems lies a deepening European productivity problem.
As a result of the “green” energy directives enacted by Brussels – a code for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the wage bills in the world do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, there is a revolt, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, France’s political elite saw the EU as a vehicle with which to keep Germany in check and lift Paris at eye level with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy, and Europe has pushed its own economic policy, which the French economy has to fight against.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, EU-hostile Front National has just won a crucial by-election, thus putting the ruling socialists in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume a split in the right spectrum would automatically mean benefits for the left.
What does Le Pen do with her newly gained popularity among the white French working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and this is very well possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to make: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the common currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will rather become something like the “Europe of (sovereign) nations” favoured by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may hold on to the euro, but France and Southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project in the hope of flattering itself with the US.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all of this?
We can decide to be a region of (ultimately) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – which includes telling Berlin and Brussels what they can hide.
I suspect that Scotland could drive very well in a looser European union, provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same to Norway and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and made) cuts that Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to get an austerity policy from Berlin and Brussels.
Early Puberty: Growing Up Faster
African American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not yet directly mean puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible.
Experts believe epidemic obesity is a trigger for early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children’s health and family issues.
Should a mother be concerned if her daughter is already growing breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the American Academy of Pediatrics’ annual conference this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and represented a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – usually that’s not a sign that puberty is coming fast,” Kaplowitz explained.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and axillary hair, as well as body odor, appear earlier in girls.
Nevertheless, there was only a slight shift in the age of the menarche (occurrence of first regular bleeding) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
“When breast development begins, it takes at least two to three years until menarche,” said Kaplowitz, also author of the book “Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Dealing with This Frequently Occurring Problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It’s controversial what actually represents the onset of puberty, but it’s “premature” when breast augmentation is accompanied by a growth spurt eight years ago.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates – something that a pediatrician can closely monitor.
With faster progress, tests by an endocronologist could be indicated so that serious problems such as tumors or cysts can be ruled out.
There are treatment methods to delay early menstruation and the defense of another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for a drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the speed of development, the rate of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is reluctant when it comes to medication, but he admits: “Suppressing puberty can alleviate behavioral problems and girls’ feelings of being different from their peers.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have the period.
“They are worried about the risk of pregnancy or about how they handle the hygienic side,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” remembers a woman whose daughter had ten days.
Even though there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home scared and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are causal.
Boys come into puberty like girls did before.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported a 2001 study of girls between the ages of six and nine, which establishes a link between body fat and puberty.
Other studies support this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another riddle: Although boys’ facial and pubic hair grows earlier, the trend towards a full-fledged earlier puberty is not as pronounced as it is for girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference emphasized the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and toddlers.
“We need to be careful how we identify the true beginning of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This may mean that you have to have a conversation sooner than expected,” Kaplowitz said.
If you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who bloom early need the assurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than intended.
