Airbus says its rival sticks to a seating concept from the 1950s, when the average body circumference of the newly named “Jet Set” was narrower.
According to Airbus, studies have shown that an additional inch (2.54 cm) per seat increases the quality of sleep by 53 percent.
Boeing disputes Airbus’s figures on seat sizes and says it is not in the discretion of manufacturers to decide how airlines balance flight tariffs with facilities.
The company also explains that according to research, the experience on the plane depends on more than the seat width.
