On the other hand, analysts say full cabins with ten seats per row at existing 777s suggested that many passengers opted for the tighter arrangement, which could come with cheaper airfares.
“Eighteen inches of seat width would be great for passengers, but the reality is: from an economic point of view, the Airbus offering is driven by the threat posed by the 777,” says Mary Kirby, cabin equipment expert, founder and publisher of Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not offer seats, but a catalog of suppliers from which the airlines can choose.
The world-travelling jet sellers even carry tape measure to measure the facility with the competition.
Even if they value comfort, all manufacturers also offer high-density jets for low-cost airlines and regional flights.
Airbus offers an A350 with ten-seat rows, but has not yet sold one, according to its own statement.
Until recently, Airbus has emphasized the importance of more adaptability of the cabins and offered wide seats at the corridors for some jets.
