New Anti-Nicotine Vaccine Could Make the Pleasure of Smoking Go Out
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could spoil the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine could protect mice from nicotine addiction for a lifetime.
Before human testing, further trials are needed, which may take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the first results were good.
“We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can once help millions of smokers who have tried to quit trying all the methods available on the market, but have had to experience that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches,” said Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information for the production of nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies hunt down the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, so a smoker does not experience nicotine high.
In experiments, vaccinated mice who were given nicotine maintained their normal activity level.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, would have taken a "out of time", the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The vaccinations had to be given so often to maintain antibody levels that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be significantly lower, as it transforms liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for humans, if it is safe to give to children before they are tempted to try a cigarette, could prevent nicotine addiction.
But more likely, smokers would use it to quit.
“Then they know that when they start smoking again, they don’t enjoy it anymore because of the nicotine vaccine, and that helps them to quit the habit,” he explains.
