Households are booming in Singapore as the crisis has arrived in the middle class
In a penthouse in Singapore’s Bendemeer shopping mall, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a gold bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay her daughters’ school fees.
“My husband and I just bought a house, and all my money is in it,” says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars (about <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1,730) each month as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
In fact, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – is so high that ValueMax, where it has made its exchange, this week became the third mortgage listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
Loaning jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – $1,300 in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, mortgages in Singapore require an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, which is just over the 15.4 percent that the United Overseas Bank requires, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, mortgages offer the advantage that no credit check or proof of income is required, which is why loans are possible faster than banks.
For this reason, millions of people in the region are turning to mortgages after families feel the pressure from rising living costs as well as an increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a loose financial policy in developed economies, lower- and middle-income families are looking for mortgages to make up for the difference in a stuttering economy.
This week, the credit rating agency Standard & Poor's noted that growing household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, is a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore, according to the agency, have the highest household debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also worried about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which has barely emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed an ongoing export weakness and a decline in consumer demand.
“Ultimately, this means that, given rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical highs in gold prices over the past two years have further intensified the trend to pledge personal items, as people take the opportunity to turn the jewelry of the family into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city’s 200 pennies are gold.
People say to themselves, “The gold price looks good, let’s get Grandma’s gold chain pledged and get it back next month.”
The largest Thai mortgage operator, EasyMoney, has seen 20 percent customer growth in its branches in recent months.
The growth in the bond business is so strong that ValueMax, operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only to neighbouring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, said ValueMax CEO Yeah Lee Ching.
The company finances this with 60 percent of the $66 million it took this week with the Singapore Stock Exchange.
While some lenders have fallen into the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yeah explains that mortgages not only offer cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also do not directly increase debt.
“Customers borrow items they already own, and the liquidity of personal valuables does not increase budget evasion,” she explains.
The mortgage lending business is increasingly accepted as short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use mortgages are in financial trouble.
Wealthy people from Singapore also come to ValueMax stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from all walks of life come to us.
“These include wealthy people who borrow something for a business or investment in the short term, or small businesses that need to bridge cash flow bottlenecks,” says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
