FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in airplanes (but not carry out cell phone calls)
Air travelers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies, but not use their cell phones, according to the new guidelines issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States on Thursday.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented, depending on the respective airline, FAA staffer Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines must prove to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the flight crew training manuals and equipment storage regulations in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
“Depending on the status of the plan, we could approve the extended use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers have to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They are only allowed to restart it when the aircraft has reached a height of three kilometers and gives the captain a green light.
When entering the landing, passengers must turn it off again and are not allowed to start it again before the plane has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are insured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even when taking off, landing and on the runway, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft re-equipped to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the Professional Flight Companion Association, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is implemented safely – and we are working closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit,” Glading said.
To be honest, we are tired of having to feel like caretakers in this matter.
Internet connections for surfing, exchanging emails, text messages or downloading data under three kilometers remained prohibited, the agency said.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still no “Words With Friends,” the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he publicly had to leave an American Airlines jet because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the landing.
And heavier devices such as laptops still need to be stowed, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight will also remain prohibited.
The regulatory authority for telephone calls is the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices on take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national traffic safety expert on CBS News, said mobile phones would still be considered a risk.
“Handys are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause interference with navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also interfere with transmitter masts,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate the issue recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has increased on the FAA to ease restrictions on use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri believe there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
In some studies, it is said that up to one-third of passengers forget or ignore turning off the device.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air passengers in 1966 after reports of malfunctions of navigation and communication devices by passenger-carrying FM radios, which were the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more reliant on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA that they don’t care about electronic interference.
Airlines have been providing passengers with Wi-Fi for several years when the flight height has been reached.
The aircraft adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for greater use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only emit minimal radiation when flipping around.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transfer values are stronger.
Amazon.com is a proponent of loosening restrictions on the use of the device by passengers.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle E-readers and made a test flight to identify problems, but could not detect any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believed the malfunction was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there were only occasional reports of pilots talking about a malfunction of aircraft systems through the devices, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to arrange for the disablement of the devices by the passengers in the event of instrument landing in poor visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable adaptation for travelers who would today be extensively equipped with technology.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not at odds with safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
