But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “In humans, it is well known that the left and right half of the brain respond differently to stimuli that elicit positive or negative emotions.”
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just as in humans, the right half of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the lateral tail buds of their peers, the researchers monitored the animals while watching these films of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged and analyzed the behavior.
We’ll probably soon understand why the cock moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs movies with dogs – either a lifelike version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressionless dog moved the tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the wagging dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail tilted mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog that wedges), then their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs had learned from experience which movements they should worry about and when not.
He said: “If you have different encounters with other dogs and the wedge with the tail is linked in one direction to friendly behavior, and the right side is more likely to produce less friendly behavior, then you react based on these experiences.”
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand their animal’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert in dog behavior and guest fellow at the University of Bristol’s Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to examine whether left and right dogs were important.
