On the way through mud, rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical care to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
In the West African country there are not many doctors, only one for 5,000 people
Tune in here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 “CNN Heroes of 2013”.
You can vote for him or one of the other heroes in the top 10 to elect him as “CNN Hero of the Year”.
The winner receives $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched as his sick father repeatedly lost consciousness and traveled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first he had only one broken arm, but then an inflammation formed that spread to his brain and there caused a hematoma that would affect him for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
“It’s not easy,” Bwelle comments.
You can leave the house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and it's not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwell’s father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, in the United States, the ratio for a doctor is 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford the visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three-quarters of the country’s health spending is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
To see his father and so many of his compatriots suffer, Bwelle made the decision to do something about it ripe.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team have performed 700 free surgeries over the past year.
He became a physician himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people force themselves in minibuses and drive with the corded medical equipment on the roof over unfortunate terrain to the villages in need of help.
Not always everything goes smoothly.
Already more than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted like heroes: a feast, singing and dancing and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and wave – with its wide smile and its limitless energy – is happy to attend the joyful celebration.
The next morning, the team will start examining hundreds of patients.
“We treat 500 people per trip,” says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village – and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates – a document that is required for school, but many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The surgeries usually take place in a school, town hall, or apartment; after the surgery, patients get up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next.
The lighting for the operation and the disinfection equipment is fed by the generator of the group and thus Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early morning hours on Sunday.
It’s an exhausting schedule, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
“They’ve been drumming all night so we can stay awake and continue our work,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team then drives back to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group – a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – has carried out 700 free surgeries over the past year and knows that its work makes a huge difference to the people it helps.
One man explained that the free operation of a leprosy he received now allows him to work again.
“This will change the future of my family,” he said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his non-profit activity, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
“I really don’t know when he’s sleeping,” says Katie O’Malley, who is a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteers with Bwell’s group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so that he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O’Malley, who come from the US and Europe and support Bwelle, this is an opportunity to gain hands-on experience that they would never get at home.
“We can be in surgeries where we help drain blood or hold the instruments for Dr. Bwell,” O’Malley explains.
That would never be possible in America as a second-year medical student.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated medical supplies with them.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transportation and guidance.
“He’s definitely a hero,” says O’Malley.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no bounds.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life and thus fulfilling a promise he made to his father brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this work,” says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
Visit the ASCOVIME website and find out how you can help.
