Tourism: Descending to the Romans
At a length of about 120 meters, a Roman-era sewage canal is preserved below Cologne.
Those who visit Cologne will not pass the cathedral.
Around 157 meters, the two towers protrude into the sky and make it the second tallest church building in Europe.
But few visitors who admire the two filigree church towers suspect that there is a lot to discover even under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert on the Cologne underworld.
The meeting point for his guided tours is the service center of Cologne-Tourismus directly at the cathedral.
The tour begins quite unspectacularly: "We start in the underground garage," says Schulze.
In the 1970s, the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore only what was not too big remained of the remains of the old city walls.
Therefore, most users of the car park today also rush past the Roman remains and stop only their car.
But if you take a closer look, you will discover an archaeological site separated by metal lattice rods in the park deck D2.
You can see about five meters high ruins of handteller-sized stones.
“These are remnants of the Roman city wall that was built in the second half of the first century AD,” Schulze says.
Before it goes back to daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper level of the park take another look into a dark, 15-metre-deep shaft.
This is the fountain of the old dome, which unfortunately is hardly perceived.
The next stop of the tour is the Praetorium, and here the participants descend back into the depths.
We experience here the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the praetor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means as much as "City of the Roman Right and City of the Agrippinians, founded under Emperor Claudius at the place of the altar for the imperial cult".
And the praetorium is the former Governor's Palace, the power center of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the exhibition hallway, a tunnel leads to the Roman sewage canal, which is preserved here at about 120 meters in length.
"You can walk a bit along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze cheers the guests on.
There's a surprise for Schulze.
After picking up the key at the checkout, he leads the group to a 16-meter deep, walkable shaft.
“We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath,” he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep in the ground to get to the groundwater, which was essential for the ritual washings.
To this day, at the lower end of the mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will be part of an archaeological zone on the Town Hall Square, for which construction work will begin shortly.
However, it will be a few more years before it is completed.
