John Kerry, with an unexpected admission, hinted at a shift in the U.S.’s defensive stance with respect to its surveillance programs, saying the espionage had “inappropriately gone too far” in certain cases.
The foreign minister also admitted that he, along with Barack Obama, was responsible for switching to “autopilot” when the explosive revelations of whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s espionage activities were made public.
The leaked information has led the US government into a diplomatic storm of indignation on the part of its allies.
